Introduction

This document shows the process of transforming, organizing, and modifying data to extract meaningful insights or fulfill specific requirements. It involves various operations and techniques applied to data, such as filtering, sorting, aggregating, merging, splitting, and transforming.

Loading packages

library(tidyverse)
library(gapminder)
library(MASS)
library(forcats)

Loading both tidyverse and MASS packages causes Error if select function is used, to solve it dplyr::select was used instead of select.

Manipulate data using the tidyverse

head(starwars)
## # A tibble: 6 x 14
##   name      height  mass hair_color skin_color eye_color birth_year sex   gender
##   <chr>      <int> <dbl> <chr>      <chr>      <chr>          <dbl> <chr> <chr> 
## 1 Luke Sky~    172    77 blond      fair       blue            19   male  mascu~
## 2 C-3PO        167    75 <NA>       gold       yellow         112   none  mascu~
## 3 R2-D2         96    32 <NA>       white, bl~ red             33   none  mascu~
## 4 Darth Va~    202   136 none       white      yellow          41.9 male  mascu~
## 5 Leia Org~    150    49 brown      light      brown           19   fema~ femin~
## 6 Owen Lars    178   120 brown, gr~ light      blue            52   male  mascu~
## # i 5 more variables: homeworld <chr>, species <chr>, films <list>,
## #   vehicles <list>, starships <list>
starwars %>% 
  dplyr::select(gender, mass, height, species) %>% 
  filter(species == "Human") %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  mutate(height = height/100) %>% 
  mutate(BMI = mass / height^2) %>% 
  group_by(gender) %>% 
  summarise(Average_BMI = mean(BMI))
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   gender    Average_BMI
##   <chr>           <dbl>
## 1 feminine         22.0
## 2 masculine        26.0

Using the tidyverse and dplyr packages to create a new variable

sw_2 <- starwars %>% 
  dplyr::select(name, height, mass, gender) %>% 
  rename(weight = mass) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  mutate(height = height/100) %>% 
  filter(gender == "masculine" |
           gender == "feminine")
head(sw_2)
## # A tibble: 6 x 4
##   name           height weight gender   
##   <chr>           <dbl>  <dbl> <chr>    
## 1 Luke Skywalker   1.72     77 masculine
## 2 C-3PO            1.67     75 masculine
## 3 R2-D2            0.96     32 masculine
## 4 Darth Vader      2.02    136 masculine
## 5 Leia Organa      1.5      49 feminine 
## 6 Owen Lars        1.78    120 masculine
sw_3 <- starwars %>% 
  dplyr::select(name, height, mass, gender) %>% 
  rename(weight = mass) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  mutate(height = height/100) %>% 
  filter(gender %in% c("masculine", "feminine")) %>% 
  mutate(gender = recode(gender,
                         masculine = "m",
                         feminine = "f")) %>% 
  mutate(size = if_else(height > 1 & weight > 75, "big", "small"))
head(sw_3)
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
##   name           height weight gender size 
##   <chr>           <dbl>  <dbl> <chr>  <chr>
## 1 Luke Skywalker   1.72     77 m      big  
## 2 C-3PO            1.67     75 m      small
## 3 R2-D2            0.96     32 m      small
## 4 Darth Vader      2.02    136 m      big  
## 5 Leia Organa      1.5      49 f      small
## 6 Owen Lars        1.78    120 m      big

  filter(marital %in% c("Never married",
                        "Married",
                        "Widowed")) %>% 
  count(age, marital) %>% 
  group_by(age) %>% 
  mutate(prop = n / sum(n)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = prop, colour = marital)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 2, na.rm = TRUE) +
  theme_minimal()

# Reordering factors by its value corresponding 
# to the largest x value
gss_cat %>% 
  filter(!is.na(age)) %>% 
  filter(marital %in% c("Never married",
                        "Married",
                        "Widowed")) %>% 
  count(age, marital) %>% 
  group_by(age) %>% 
  mutate(prop = n / sum(n)) %>% 
  mutate(marital = fct_reorder2(marital, age, prop)) %>% 
  mutate(marital = fct_rev(marital)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = prop, colour = marital)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 2, na.rm = TRUE) +
  theme_minimal()
